@node intro "Introduction"
@{fg shine}
 >>> INTRODUCTION
@{fg text}
 @{b}OrderForm@{ub} is a program for ShareWare (and even Commercial) programmers.
 It allows you to include an "order form" for potential purchasers of your
 software/programs in your archives or demo distribution disks.

 For example, imagine you downloaded an archive from Aminet, and are happy
 with the software enough to want to purchase it.  You then have to write
 yourself an order form for it, or if the author was kind enough, he'll have
 already written an ASCII template for you to fill out.

 This is where @{b}OrderForm@{ub} comes in!  It's an actual program that authors can
 include in their Aminet (or other) archives, with all details of payment
 and pricing of their program built-in.  The purchaser runs this program,
 puts his name to it, selects what he wants of the program (eg: version,
 format, etc), and then clicks a gadget to print it all out.  He then mails
 this order to the author who sends back the program in return.  Simple!

 @{b}OrderForm@{ub} makes use of GadTools (the Workbench 2.04+ GUI system) to save
 memory and work quickly.  The window is also fully font-sensitive as all
 good programs should be.  :)

 Now some info for ShareWare/Commercial authors who may be interested in
 using @{b}OrderForm@{ub} with their distributed demos:

 The @{b}OrderForm@{ub} program is 99% customisable to your product, in these ways:

  · Gets purchaser's full name and address, including E-Mail if needed.

  · Allows purchaser to order your program from 1 of 3 formats: Floppy Disk,
    E-Mail (eg: UUEncoded), or CD-ROM.  If you can only handle floppies, the
    E-Mail/CD-ROM selections are automatically ghosted and unselectable.

  · The author can set individual prices for each format, as well as for
    International or Local postage charges.

  · Allows purchaser to pay from 5 different methods: Cash, Check, Money
    Order, MasterCard, Visa Card.  If you can't handle credit cards, they
    won't be available for purchasers to select.

  · Allows purchaser to specify which version of your program they want (if
    you have more than one, eg: 68000, 68020+, 68060 Only, etc).

  · Allows purchaser to fill out a 7-Question "interview" that gives info
    to the author about the purchaser's opinions and Amiga specifications.
    This gives valuable "market research" data to the author that can help
    with future updates of his product.

  · Completed order forms can be printed to the PRT: device for Snail Mail
    postage, or to a disk file for E-Mail submission.

 Basically, @{b}OrderForm@{ub} is a @{i}must@{ui} for all ShareWare/Commercial programmers.

 There are actually two programs involved:

 @{"OrderForm" link usag1} - This is what you distribute with your programs that potential
              purchasers use to fill out their order.
 @{"FormMaker" link usag2} - This is what you use to generate the @{b}OrderForm@{ub} that gets
              distributed.

 Both are explained elsewhere in this document, so read on!
@{fg shine}
 ===========================================================================
@endnode
@node requi "Requirements"
@{fg shine}
 >>> REQUIREMENTS
@{fg text}
 @{"OrderForm" link usag1} and @{"FormMaker" link usag2} require the following items to run:

  · Any Amiga running Workbench 2.04 or higher
  · ReqTools.library (click @{"here" link rtool} for more info)

 However, that's not all: As a programmer, @{i}you@{ui} have a few requirements to
 fulfill before you can use @{b}OrderForm@{ub}...

 IF YOU OFFER:           THEN YOU @{i}MUST@{ui} BE ABLE TO SUPPLY:

 Floppy distribution     WB 1.3 OFS and WB 2.04+ FFS formatted disks.
 E-Mail distribution     UUEncoded and MIME Encoded E-Mails.
 CD-ROM distribution     Normal ISO-9660 and CD32-Compatible discs.

 The Floppy and E-Mail distributions are easy to supply, but what do I mean
 by "ISO-9660" and "CD32-Compatible" for CD-ROM distribution?  Well, 99% of
 CD-ROM's for the Amiga are in ISO-9660 format, which means virtually all
 CD-ROM drives (including the CD32) can read them.  However, there's a tiny
 minority of CD-ROM formats that the CD32 @{i}can't@{ui} read.  To prevent someone
 from ordering such a format for their CD32 (and thus getting disappointed
 because it won't work), the @{b}OrderForm@{ub} program allows them to specifically
 state that the CD-ROM must be "CD32-Compatible".  It's then up to you to
 ensure that the CD you send @{i}does@{ui} work on a CD32... If you can't test this,
 then be prepared to refund their money, just in case.  :)
@{fg shine}
 ===========================================================================
@endnode
@node amiga "Compatibility"
@{fg shine}
 >>> COMPATIBILITY
@{fg text}
 Firstly, I'll assume you've read the @{"requirements" link requi} section...?  Good!

 Both @{"OrderForm" link usag1} and @{"FormMaker" link usag2} have only been tested on one Amiga, since
 that's all the @{"author" link autho} has access to.  It has the following configuration:

  · Amiga 1200, Workbench 3.1, AGA Chipset, 68020, 2 MB Chip, 4 MB Fast.

 Thus, the author can absolutely, positively, @{i}guarantee without question@{ui}
 that @{b}OrderForm@{ub} and @{b}FormMaker@{ub} will run on such a system.  :)

 Anyway, if either program crashes on @{i}your@{ui} system, try the following:

  · Ensure @{b}ReqTools.library@{ub} is installed on your @{i}original@{ui} Workbench disk.
  · Boot from your original Workbench disk.
  · Run the offending program.

 The program @{i}should@{ui} now run without hassle.  It does on the author's Amiga,
 when he performs the same three steps as above.  If you @{i}still@{ui} encounter
 problems, then I'm afraid it's not due to the program, but definitely due
 to something else you have installed which is clashing with it.
@{fg shine}
 ===========================================================================
@endnode
@node rtool "ReqTools.library"
@{fg shine}
 >>> WHAT THE HECK IS "REQTOOLS.LIBRARY" ?
@{fg text}
 @{b}ReqTools.library@{ub} is what you might consider a "system enhancer" for your
 Amiga.  Basically, it's a file that many programs use that enable them to
 provide "requesters" of all shapes and sizes.  In fact, it's so popular
 that you might already have it installed in your system!

 If you run @{"OrderForm" link usag1} and get an error message saying that @{b}ReqTools.library@{ub}
 is not installed, then unfortunately you don't have it yet.  You'll have to
 download it from Aminet: its name is @{b}ReqToolsUsr.lha@{ub} and it's found in the
 @{b}util/libs@{ub} directory.  Install it as soon as possible, because a great deal
 of Amiga software makes use of it these days.
@{fg shine}
 ===========================================================================
@endnode
@node usag1 "Using OrderForm"
@{fg shine}
 >>> USING ORDERFORM
@{fg text}
 Double-click the @{b}OrderForm@{ub} icon and have a play with the example options
 that appear.  Then, write the order form to a disk file (use the default of
 "RAM:OrderForm.txt").  Lastly, read this disk file to see what the final
 order form looks like from your purchaser's point-of-view.

 What you've just done is what your potential purchasers will do.  See how
 easy it is for them to order your programs with @{b}OrderForm@{ub}?

 @{b}OrderForm@{ub} works from ToolTypes.  That is, when you just double-clicked the
 @{b}OrderForm@{ub} executable, the example data was stored in the icon's ToolTypes.
 At this point you may say that potential purchasers can easily edit such
 data, but so what?  I can just as easily laser-print a new price on any
 coupon from any magazine in the same way.  And since your program will most
 likely be downloaded from Aminet or something similar, you have a permanent
 legal copy with which to prove your original pricing details.  So relax.

 The data stored in the ToolTypes can be hand-edited if you like, but I
 wouldn't recommend it.  I've written a special program to do the work for
 you, called @{"FormMaker" link usag2}.  Run it and it will ask you a range of questions
 and then write the ToolTypes into the @{b}OrderForm@{ub} icon automatically.  This
 makes it all much easier and errors are impossible to generate.
@{fg shine}
 ===========================================================================
@endnode
@node usag2 "Using FormMaker"
@{fg shine}
 >>> USING FORM MAKER
@{fg text}
 Firstly, make sure the @{b}OrderForm@{ub} program is in the same drawer as the
 @{b}FormMaker@{ub} program.  This is necessary because @{b}FormMaker@{ub} writes directly to
 the @{b}OrderForm@{ub} icon and expects it to be in the same drawer.  Similarly,
 ensure that the @{b}OrderForm@{ub} program is not renamed to anything else.

 To create your own custom order form, double-click @{b}FormMaker@{ub}.  The process
 is now fully automatic, with the program asking you simple questions which
 you answer correctly.  Don't make a mistake, because you can't go back.
 If you do make a mistake, quit the program and start again.

 When entering money amounts, just enter the digits and don't use dollar
 signs or anything.  For example, to specify @{b}$49.95@{ub}, enter @{b}49.95@{ub} only.

 Everything is fairly self-explanatory so you shouldn't get into trouble.
 Just do what's asked of you and all should be fine.  You can always E-Mail
 @{"me" link autho} if you need help with anything, but I doubt you will.

 Remember to test your order form by running the @{b}OrderForm@{ub} program after
 you've finished making it.  If it works okay, you can then copy @{b}OrderForm@{ub}
 to your own distribution archives for your own purchasers' use.  Make sure
 you @{i}don't@{ui} include the @{b}FormMaker@{ub} program though, and don't forget to pay
 your @{"ShareWare" link share} fee first!  :)
@{fg shine}
 ===========================================================================
@endnode
@node restr "Restrictions"
@{fg shine}
 >>> RESTRICTIONS
@{fg text}
 There are 3 things that you can't do with @{b}OrderForm@{ub} at the moment:

  · You can't set a postage price for sending an E-Mail order.  This is
    logical because there's no postal charges for sending E-Mail (yet).

  · You can't order more than one copy of a format with @{b}OrderForm@{ub}.  That is,
    purchasers can only buy 1 x Floppy, 1 x E-Mail and 1 x CD-ROM per order.
    I doubt this would be a hassle, but if so, then the purchaser will just
    have to submit the order as many times as necessary.

  · You can't specify payment in a format other than the 5 provided (Cash,
    Check, Money Order, MasterCard, Visa Card).  Some programmers like their
    clients to pay by @{b}Giro@{ub} but the @{"author" link autho} doesn't understand what this is
    (which is why it isn't an option).  If you'd like to explain it, E-Mail
    him and it'll be included in a future release of @{b}OrderForm@{ub}.  The same
    goes for any other major payment methods.
@{fg shine}
 ===========================================================================
@endnode
@node share "ShareWare/Legal"
@{fg shine}
 >>> SHAREWARE / LEGAL
@{fg text}
 @{b}OrderForm@{ub} took 3 consecutive days to write, involving preliminary window
 GUI design and price calculations, to bugfixes, enhancements, and more
 bugfixes.  Then this AmigaGuide document took a 4th day to write, because
 such documents aren't exactly quick to write either.

 Thus, @{b}OrderForm@{ub} is a ShareWare program, meaning that you @{i}must@{ui} pay for it
 if you intend to include it in your program's demo release.  However, it
 is unprotected ShareWare, allowing you to avoid paying the @{"author" link autho} if you
 feel dishonest - it's up to you.  But be warned: @{b}OrderForm@{ub} has a message
 stating that it hasn't been paid for; and thus potential purchasers of your
 program may not pay up if they see you didn't pay for @{b}OrderForm@{ub} yourself!

 Being ShareWare means @{b}OrderForm@{ub} is also © 1997 by Paul Bowlay (the author).
 This means you @{i}can't@{ui} alter any of its data without his written permission
 or sell it for any profit.  It also means it's Freely Distributable (such
 as on Aminet) but you are @{i}not@{ui} allowed to distribute it commercially (except
 on Aminet CD's) or include it as part of a commercial package.

 The ShareWare fee is @{b}$20 Australian Dollars@{ub}.  You can @{i}only@{ui} pay this with
 @{i}Australian Currency@{ui} after contacting the author first to get his mailing
 address.  Once payment is received, you will receive a new copy of the
 program that has your name registered to it, and thus shows your potential
 purchasers that you're an honest and reputable person.  :)

 If you don't know where to get Australian Currency, try your local travel
 agency or bank.  I know it's a hassle but that's simply the way it is.

 (One alternative to paying the ShareWare fee is to offer me a registered
 copy of one of @{i}your@{ui} programs.  An eye for an eye, so to speak.  But don't
 get your hopes up, because I'm extremely picky about what I like).

 Once paid, you can use @{b}OrderForm@{ub} for as many of your programs as you like.
 It's a single fee that gives you exclusive right to that copy of @{b}OrderForm@{ub}
 forever.  However, if you change your name or company name, you will have
 to pay a @{i}new@{ui} $20 fee to cover the cost of me coding a new copy and sending
 it to you.

 Finally, do @{i}not@{ui} give your registered copies of @{b}OrderForm@{ub} to anyone else
 to use with their programs.  Doing so is software piracy and I will find
 out and sue the pants off you.  :)  Seriously, I will.
@{fg shine}
 ===========================================================================
@endnode
